Q.  D/f b/w Package.json OR Package.lock.json ?
A.  package.json - 
    🔹Stores the direct dependencies and project configuration required for the application.
    "react": "^18.2.0"
    🔹Uses version ranges (^, ~) so npm can install compatible newer versions.

    package-lock.json
    🔹Stores the exact installed version of every package, including all sub-dependencies (nested dependencies).
    "react": {
      "version": "18.2.0"
    }
    🔹Ensures same dependency installation for every developer/system by locking the complete dependency tree.




Q.  What is node_modules?
A.  node_modules is the folder that stores all installed npm packages, including direct and transitive (sub) dependencies.

    When we run:
    npm install axios
    npm installs axios along with its required sub-packages and stores all those package files inside node_modules.
    Each installed dependency inside node_modules also contains its own package.json file, because every package is itself a separate Node.js project/package.



Q.  What is the use of .gitignore?
A. .gitignore is used to tell Git which files or folders should not be tracked or pushed to the repository.
    It is commonly used to ignore:
    - node_modules/
    - environment files (.env)
    - build/generated files
    - logs or temporary files




Q.  Difference between npm and npx?
A.  npm:
    1. npm (Node Package Manager) is used to install and manage packages.
    2. It permanently installs packages into node_modules.
    Example:
    npm install react

    npx:
    1. npx (Node Package Execute) is used to directly run packages without permanently installing them.
    2. It executes the package temporarily.
    Example:
    npx create-react-app my-app
